If you’ve ever written for...of over an array and felt good about yourself, this article is going to introduce you to its more capable cousin: async iterators. They let you loop over data that arrives over time — paginated APIs, file streams, WebSocket messages, database cursors — using the same clean loop syntax you already know.
By the end of this article you’ll understand:

• What iterators and iterables are (quick recap for beginners)

• What async iterators actually are, under the hood

• for await...of and async generators

• Real-world examples: paginated API fetching, reading streams, rate-limited processing

• Error handling, cleanup, and common pitfalls

• A cheat sheet you can bookmark
1. Quick Recap: Iterators and Iterables (Skip if you know this)
Before async iterators make sense, you need to be solid on regular iterators.
An iterable is any object that has a Symbol.iterator method. Arrays, strings, Maps, and Sets are all iterables — that's why for...of works on them.
An iterator is an object with a next() method that returns { value, done }.
const numbers = [10, 20, 30];
const iterator = numbers[Symbol.iterator]();console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: 10, done: false }
console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: 20, done: false }
console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: 30, done: false }
console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: undefined, done: true }
for...of is just syntactic sugar that calls next() repeatedly until done is true.
You can make your own iterable object:
const range = {
from: 1,
to: 5,
[Symbol.iterator]() {
let current = this.from;
const last = this.to;
return {
next() {
if (current <= last) {
return { value: current++, done: false };
}
return { value: undefined, done: true };
}
};
}
};for (const num of range) {
console.log(num); // 1, 2, 3, 4, 5
}
This works great — as long as every value is available immediately. The problem starts when values arrive over time.
2. The Problem: What Happens When Values Aren’t Ready Yet?
Imagine you’re fetching pages of data from an API, or reading chunks of a file. Each “next value” depends on a network call or disk read — it’s a Promise, not an immediate value.
Regular iterators can’t return a Promise from next() and have for...of understand it. You'd have to manually await inside a loop and manage state yourself:
// The painful, manual way (before async iterators)
async function processManually(source) {
let result = await source.getNext();
while (!result.done) {
console.log(result.value);
result = await source.getNext();
}
}This works, but it’s boilerplate-heavy, error-prone, and doesn’t compose well. This is exactly the gap async iterators fill.
3. What Is an Async Iterator?
An async iterator is identical in spirit to a regular iterator, with one difference: next() returns a Promise that resolves to { value, done } instead of returning that object directly.
An async iterable is an object with a Symbol.asyncIterator method (instead of Symbol.iterator).
const asyncRange = {
from: 1,
to: 5,
[Symbol.asyncIterator]() {
let current = this.from;
const last = this.to;
return {
next() {
return new Promise((resolve) => {
setTimeout(() => {
if (current <= last) {
resolve({ value: current++, done: false });
} else {
resolve({ value: undefined, done: true });
}
}, 500); // simulate delay, e.g. network latency
});
}
};
}
};JavaScript gives you a loop built specifically for this:
async function run() {
for await (const num of asyncRange) {
console.log(num); // 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 — each printed ~500ms apart
}
}run();
for await...of automatically awaits each next() call for you. No manual Promise chaining, no manual loop-and-await boilerplate.
4. Async Generators: The Easier Way to Write Async Iterators
Writing Symbol.asyncIterator by hand, as above, is verbose. Just like generator functions (function*) make regular iterators easy to write, async generator functions (async function*) make async iterators easy to write.
async function* asyncRangeGenerator(from, to) {
for (let i = from; i <= to; i++) {
await new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, 500));
yield i;
}
}async function run() {
for await (const num of asyncRangeGenerator(1, 5)) {
console.log(num);
}
}
run();
That’s it. async function* handles all the Symbol.asyncIterator plumbing for you. This is the pattern you'll use 95% of the time in real code — you rarely hand-write the raw iterator protocol.
Rule of thumb:

• Need to await something before producing a value? Use async function*.

• Producing values instantly/synchronously? A regular generator (function*) is enough.
5. Real-World Example 1: Paginated API Fetching
This is the single most common real-world use case. Say you’re hitting an API that returns 20 results per page, and you want to process all results without manually managing page numbers everywhere in your code.
async function* fetchAllUsers(baseUrl) {
let page = 1;
let hasMore = true; while (hasMore) {
const response = await fetch(`${baseUrl}?page=${page}&limit=20`);
const data = await response.json();
for (const user of data.users) {
yield user; // yield one user at a time, not the whole page
}
hasMore = data.users.length === 20; // assume fewer results means last page
page++;
}
}
async function main() {
for await (const user of fetchAllUsers('https://api.example.com/users')) {
console.log(`Processing user: ${user.name}`);
// do something per user — save to DB, transform, etc.
}
}
main();
Notice what this buys you: the calling code (main) has no idea pagination is happening. It just sees a stream of users. The pagination logic is fully encapsulated inside the generator. This is the real power of async iterators — they decouple "how data arrives" from "what you do with each item."
Real scenario: At a fintech company, this exact pattern is used to reconcile transactions against a payment provider’s API that paginates results. Instead of a nested loop juggling page++ and hasMore flags in business logic, the sync/reconciliation code just does for await (const txn of fetchAllTransactions()).
6. Real-World Example 2: Reading a Stream Chunk by Chunk
Node.js streams and the Web Streams API (used by fetch response bodies) are natively async iterable.
Reading a large file line by line in Node.js:
import { createReadStream } from 'fs';
import { createInterface } from 'readline';async function processLargeFile(filePath) {
const fileStream = createReadStream(filePath);
const rl = createInterface({ input: fileStream, crlfDelay: Infinity });
let lineNumber = 0;
for await (const line of rl) {
lineNumber++;
if (line.includes('ERROR')) {
console.log(`Line ${lineNumber}: ${line}`);
}
}
}
processLargeFile('./server.log');
This reads a log file of any size — a few KB or several GB — without loading the whole thing into memory. That’s the core benefit: async iterators let you process infinite or huge data sources with constant memory usage.
Reading a fetch response body as a stream (browser or Node 18+):
async function streamResponse(url) {
const response = await fetch(url);
const reader = response.body.getReader();
const decoder = new TextDecoder(); while (true) {
const { done, value } = await reader.read();
if (done) break;
console.log(decoder.decode(value));
}
}
Real scenario: This pattern is used for streaming LLM chat responses — like ChatGPT’s token-by-token typing effect. The server sends chunks as they’re generated, and the client reads and renders each chunk the moment it arrives, instead of waiting for the entire response.
7. Real-World Example 3: Rate-Limited / Throttled Processing
Say you need to call a third-party API that allows only 1 request per second, for a list of 1,000 items. Async generators make this trivial to express.
function delay(ms) {
return new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, ms));
}async function* rateLimitedProcessor(items, delayMs) {
for (const item of items) {
const result = await callExternalApi(item);
yield result;
await delay(delayMs); // wait before yielding the next one
}
}
async function callExternalApi(item) {
// simulate an API call
return { item, processedAt: Date.now() };
}
async function main() {
const items = Array.from({ length: 1000 }, (_, i) => i + 1);
for await (const result of rateLimitedProcessor(items, 1000)) {
console.log('Processed:', result.item);
}
}
main();
No setInterval juggling, no external queue library needed. The throttling logic lives right next to the thing being throttled, and the consumer code (main) stays completely clean.
8. Error Handling in Async Iteration
Wrap your for await...of loop in a normal try/catch — errors thrown inside the generator (or in a fetch call, etc.) propagate out naturally.
async function* riskyGenerator() {
yield 1;
yield 2;
throw new Error('Something went wrong at item 3');
yield 3; // never reached
}async function main() {
try {
for await (const val of riskyGenerator()) {
console.log(val);
}
} catch (err) {
console.error('Caught:', err.message);
}
}
main();
// Logs: 1, 2, then "Caught: Something went wrong at item 3"
Cleanup with finally (important for real resources)
If you break out of a for await...of loop early, or an error occurs, JavaScript automatically calls the generator's return() method — which triggers any finally block inside the generator. This is critical when your generator holds open a resource like a file handle or DB connection.
async function* readRecords(connection) {
try {
while (true) {
const record = await connection.fetchNext();
if (!record) return;
yield record;
}
} finally {
console.log('Closing connection — cleanup guaranteed');
await connection.close();
}
}async function main(connection) {
for await (const record of readRecords(connection)) {
if (record.id === 5) {
break; // even here, the generator's `finally` still runs
}
console.log(record);
}
}
9. Common Pitfalls (Advanced Gotchas)
Pitfall 1: for await...of runs sequentially, not in parallel
async function* slowGen() {
yield await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(() => r(1), 1000));
yield await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(() => r(2), 1000));
}// This takes ~2 seconds total, NOT ~1 second — iterations are sequential by design
for await (const val of slowGen()) {
console.log(val);
}
If you actually want parallelism, you need Promise.all on independently-created promises, not async iteration — async iterators are inherently sequential, one value at a time.
Pitfall 2: Mixing Symbol.iterator and Symbol.asyncIterator
An object can technically define both. for...of picks Symbol.iterator; for await...of prefers Symbol.asyncIterator but falls back to Symbol.iterator if the async one is missing. Don't rely on this fallback for anything performance-sensitive — be explicit about which one you're implementing.
Pitfall 3: Forgetting that async generators are still “pull-based”
Nothing happens until you actually iterate. Calling fetchAllUsers() doesn't fetch anything — it just returns an async generator object. The first fetch call only fires when you call .next() (directly, or via for await...of). This is different from something like an RxJS Observable, which can be push-based.
When to reach for async iterators:

• Paginated API results

• Reading files/streams chunk by chunk

• Rate-limited or throttled processing of a list

• Any “infinite” or unbounded data source (e.g., a live event feed)

• Database cursors returning rows in batches
Conclusion
Async iterators solve a very specific, very common problem: looping over data that isn’t all available up front. Once you internalize that async function* + for await...of is just "generators, but each yield can wait on a Promise first," the rest falls into place naturally.
Start by rewriting one of your existing paginated-fetch functions using an async generator — you’ll immediately feel how much cleaner the calling code becomes.
